## Context

While repairing ticket 0045's corrupted body, the underlying cause
was traced to a Go slice-aliasing bug in `cmdSweepSkip` at
`tickets/tools/go/main.go:1259-1316`.

The function reads the file with `os.ReadFile` (which returns a
slice with `cap > len`), takes a sub-slice `beforeBody := raw[:idx]`
that shares the backing array, then `append`s the new log line into
`beforeBody`. Because `cap(beforeBody) == cap(raw) > idx`, `append`
mutates `raw[idx:]` in place — overwriting the `--- body ---`
separator and the first ~90 bytes of the body. The subsequent
`append(result, raw[idx+len(sep):]...)` then reads back the corrupted
bytes.

Visible symptom: the written ticket has a duplicated `--- body ---`
separator and a truncated/garbled log line at the start of the body
(e.g. line beginning `:18Z claude note sweep-skip…`).

The validator does not reject duplicate separators (rule 11 only
asserts presence, not uniqueness), so the corruption ships.

## Affected tickets

Nine tickets currently in `tickets/` carry the corruption pattern
(grep'd as files with two or more `^--- body ---$` lines):

- 0013 bib-to-zotero-skill
- 0028 multiproject-beat-dashboard
- 0034 housekeeping-split-git-and-ticket-phases
- 0042 replace-harness-rules-with-hooks
- 0043 weekly-fewer-permission-prompts
- 0045 rename-orchestrator-to-raid (already repaired manually)
- 0047 early-context-compaction-beat-raid
- 0049 truth-in-ticket-open-status
- 0051 beat-idle-project-fallback

## Actions

1. Fix `cmdSweepSkip` so it does not alias `raw`. Two viable
   options:
   - Replace `beforeBody := raw[:idx]` with
     `beforeBody := append([]byte(nil), raw[:idx]...)` (explicit
     copy), or
   - Build the result with `bytes.Buffer.Write` calls.
   The same pattern needs auditing in `cmdSweepWrite` and
   `appendToTicket`.
2. Add a Go test that round-trips a ticket through `sweep-skip`
   and asserts the body is unchanged.
3. Strengthen the validator: reject more than one `--- body ---`
   separator (rule 11 extension) so any future regression is
   caught at commit time.
4. Repair the eight remaining corrupted tickets by reading their
   pre-corruption versions from git history (each ticket's last
   non-sweep-skip commit) and re-applying the legitimate
   sweep-skip log line by hand.
5. Re-run the validator across `tickets/` and `tickets/archive/`
   to confirm zero residual corruption.

## Test

Red step: `tickets/tools/go/main_test.go` — write a ticket file
with a known body, call `cmdSweepSkip` directly, re-read the file,
assert the body matches the original byte-for-byte and there is
exactly one `--- body ---` separator.

## Exit criteria

- `cmdSweepSkip` (and any other site sharing the bug) does not
  mutate input slices.
- A Go-level regression test exists.
- The validator rejects duplicate body separators.
- All eight remaining corrupted tickets are repaired and pass
  validation.

## Out of scope

- Auditing nightbeat.log for any garbled log lines that may have
  been emitted by the same bug — log lines are append-only and the
  observed corruption is in body content.
